<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-01-06T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-01-06T18:00:00-05:00" n="2" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d2">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">711.5112 France/96: Circular
                                telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi>
                                    (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Houghton</hi></persName>)<note n="4" xml:id="d2fn4">The same
                                    telegram was sent to the Embassies in Germany, Italy, and
                                    Japan.</note></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-01-06T18:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">January
                                            6, 1928—6 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                            <p>An English translation of the proposal which Briand submitted to me
                                last June reads as follows:</p>
                            <p>[Here follows the text of the draft pact of perpetual friendship
                                contained in telegram No. 260, June 22, 1927, from the Chargé in
                                France, printed in <ref target="frus1927v02#pg_615"><hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1927, volume II, page
                                    615</ref>.]</p>
                            <p>Please deliver to the Foreign Office for the consideration of the
                                Government to which you are accredited a memorandum containing the
                                foregoing text and the text of my reply<note n="5" xml:id="d2fn5">See <ref target="frus1927v02#pg_626"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                            Relations</hi>, 1927, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>,
                                        p. 626</ref>.</note> which was telegraphed to you in the
                                Department’s circular, December 28, 8 p.m.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>